13_13	0.088235209	Water-soluble vitamins B and C do leach out of vegetables when they are cooked in liquid, but in this case they go directly into the soup.
13_14	0.10027391	To keep the vegetables from looking dead, add the most tender ones just long enough to cook and contribute some flavor without turning to mush.
13_15	0.085544164	Still another reader wanted to know how pineapple juice and carrot juice can still have fiber in them after they have been processed.
13_16	0.096481043	The best source of that kind of information is Harold McGee, the author of ``On Food and Cooking'' (Scribner, 1984).
13_17	0.072427232	As he explains, there are two kinds of fiber, soluble and insoluble.
13_18	0.091225698	Pectin, which is used to gel jellies, is soluble fiber.
13_19	0.083525076	It doesn't appear to have any texture, but it does, so you might not be able to tell it was in the juice.
13_20	0.060274791	Cellulose and lignin are insoluble fibers.
13_21	0.087412641	The fiber in a glass of pineapple or carrot juice is soluble, and it cannot be seen because it is suspended in the liquid.
13_22	0.088412351	Insoluble fiber, if it is there, is the sediment, what eventually falls to the bottom of the glass.
